text: You can complain about how kids shouldn’t be acting like this and the world is going to shit, but really, this is closer to how kids act than in most family movies. Obviously, it’s very exaggerated, but for one, most of the bad things that happen in the movie are in the trailer, and at the movie’s heart, it’s a coming of age story. I’m guessing that most of the people who are complaining about the movie didn’t actually see it, because contrary to how the trailer makes it seem, the movie isn’t just about kids doing bad things. In my opinion, I think that it’s worse to pretend that kids are innocent little angels instead of people who are starting to learn about more mature things in the world, because then the kids can make the right decisions about these more mature things, instead of hiding it and making bad decisions.

text: I saw this movie yesterday. I’m not going to lie some of it was really funny. My friends and I could relate to lots of the times when the kids freaked out, like when they crossed the highway we thought that was like us crossing at school. However lots of it was weird. Like lots of it seemed like it was for 6th graders, like the messages about friendship. The bit that I didn’t like the most though was when they go to the frat house to buy Molly. It wasn’t even the fact they were buying drugs because it is just a movie, it was the fact that there was lots of rape references, weird sorority initiation things going on and lots of dodgy men.  It just wasn’t funny to see children in that environment.  We all got ID’d to see the film even though we’re 16. My friend almost didn’t get in because she didn’t have any on her but we left and came back and someone else let us in without ID. Even though the movie has 12 year olds as the leads.  As we left lots of people said the movie was shit and I can understand why. When you’re 16/17 you don’t want to see 12 year olds crying about friendship.  I truly have no idea who the target audience is. It should be mid teens but the film is weirdly young at parts. It does deal with important issues like divorce but not very well to be honest.  Overall I did like the movie but I wouldn’t see it again any time soon. Some moments were hilarious but that’s only really because my friends and I could tag ourselves. I don’t think they’d be that funny if we couldn’t.

What's she having a threesome? What the fuck is a kissing party? That's not a thing. What the fuck are anal beads for? What's the mask for? What are the other "weapons"? What the fuck is Molly? What the fuck is a nymphomaniac? What the fuck is the indoor swing? What's it called? What's it for? This movie is appalling and despicable! If society didn't make sex and sexuality taboo and shelter kids from things, maybe I wouldn't get pissed off at movies like this. Or maybe I still would. I don't know. text: So many comments from people about how horrible this is. Labeling the people who liked the trailer as pedophiles? Really? Saying it shouldn't be available at theaters? What the? I see many people are all about censorship. We have freedoms here in the U.S. Some commenters may live in other countries where they don't have freedom of choice, but here in the U.S. a person can make a personal decision as to whether or not to watch a movie, read a book, or go to an event. In other countries the rights of people are suppressed. If you want that, I recommend you move to one of them or stay there if already in one. I personally don't like seeing (and thus avoid) the nude bicyclist events in multiple cities throughout the U.S., but since it's labeled as "progressive" those events are not only occurring, they are endorsed by the media and politicians. Somehow seeing a grown man with his appendage waving around is okay, but a movie with kids swearing and acting like most pre-teen boys is offensive? For those people who say their kid doesn't act like that, you'd be shocked. Take the rose colored glasses off. The good thing is that most of these kids grow up to be people who love their families, treat people with respect, work for a living, and have good hearts.

text: This is what middle school is like. You desperately want to grow up and yet are also terrified. Kids around you are starting to have sex and experiment with drugs and you’re still torn in between being a kid and being a teenager. Even though the kids are in adult situations, (which is what’s funny) this movie clearly shows their innocence in those situations. Hormones, puberty, moving from your family to your friend group... it’s an amazingly complicated and comic time of life. I don’t see anything wrong with it. It’s not like these kids are being led down a dark path... these things are around us all the time and all kids go through a period of learning about adult things and deciding who they want to be. Plus, It’s not aimed AT children, it’s for adults to look back on that time in their lives.
